title: Skywalker FPV pod for Propan 2 and 1.3Ghz VTX

description.text:
Here's a pod for the old style (foam tail) Skywalker that takes the Propan pan/tilt mechanism and provides a stable mounting point for a VTX.

The plate replaces the existing bottom plate of the Propan and has mounting points for the servo and standoffs.

There's also a couple of plates and a latching pin to allow the pod to be easily and securely locked into place and unlocked again.

Also included is a redesigned tilt head, as I found that the one supplied with the Propan doesn't have enough clearance to tilt successfully and the mounting point for a board cam doesn't provide nearly enough real-estate. This replacement lifts the camera height by 10mm and extends it by 10mm which is enough to provide much better tilt performance.

The Propan can be obtained here: http://fpvgadgets.com , note they're nothing to do with me, if they were they'd have a much better site that isn't as crappy to navigate.

description.text:
I made this filter holder to fit inexpensive, pleated paper coffee filters.

This general style of filter can rest on almost any convenient container. But the one I had is made to fit the cone filters, like Melitta. Cone filters are better quality, but seem to be finer (at 20 microns ?), and it takes longer to filter things.

I only needed to coarsely filter (cold) deep fryer oil into quart-size plastic containers, so I whipped this thing up. And the operation is pretty quick, filtering the big junk without taking all night to do it.

This thing will sit on containers with a maximum opening of 4 3/4 inches diameter (120 mm). Capacity is almost 16 fluid ounces (450 ml).

The internal filter support-screen is designed as a separate part, and is removable, just to make it easier to wash up.

Metric and SAE provided.

Using Afinia defaults (0.3mm layers, average speed and quality), the filter body required 4 1/2 hours, 122 grams. The screen part took about 30 min, 15 g ABS.

I printed one with external support (for the lower portion), and another without support, and couldn't detect a difference in quality. If the shallow 30 degree angle at the bottom of the filter causes trouble, and your printer can't build that angle without dripping filament over the edge, then give it some support.

description.text:
Description

This is a game for two players. The board has 16 squares (4x4), and the 16 different pieces that can be constructed combinating the following four characteristics:
•Size (big/small)
•Colour (red/blue)
•Shape (circle/ square)
•Hole (piece with hole/piece without hole)

Objective

The aim of the game is to complete a line with four pieces that are similar at least about one of the four described characteristics (four big pieces, four little, four red, four blue, four circle, four square, four with hole or four without hole). The line may be vertical, horizontal or diagonal. The winner is the player who places the fourth piece of the line.

How the game goes on

Players move alternatively, placing one piece on the board; once inserted, pieces cannot be moved.

One of the more special characteristics of this game is that the choice of the piece to be placed on the board is not made by the same player who places it; it is the opponent who, after doing his move, decides which will be the next piece to place.

So, each turn consists of two actions:

  1. Place on the board the piece given by the opponent.

  2. Give to the opponent the piece to be placed in the next move.

In the first turn of the game, the player who starts has only to choose one piece for the opponent.

Final

The game finishes in a draw when nobody reaches the objective after placing the 16 pieces.

This is a blank SCAD file that serves as the starting point when I want to create something new in OpenSCAD.

This is my own personal home-grown style for generating parts in OpenSCAD by starting with a set of positive shapes and then subtracting things from that primary shape. For complex shapes, sometimes you have to have nested sets of positives and negatives, but 90% of the parts I make are just a simple add/subtract sequence. This is how the domino generator and all of my other SCAD files started out. I hope you can learn something from this and that you find it useful for your next customizable design.

description.text:
As a mushroom fiend I found it necessary to create a printable mushroom. Unfortunately, it is not also edible. :)  
It comes in two parts: the base & stem and the cap. The second cap variation is a complete redesign with improved gills.  
Because the interlock mechanism is the same as build-a-wand the caps can also be used as finals.

These were printed using the default, standard settings in Makerware.  
Although in principal both the base and a cap can be printed at the same time, doing so takes a long time (perhaps 20 hours) and invites errors. Printing separately also allows printing in separate colors.  
This is a large model, but if printed at smaller size make sure that both cap and base are printed at the same scale. And, due to the detail for the interlock avoid printing too small. A scale of 70% has worked for other objects using this interlock.

comments.text: Hi ePoxi- it occurred to me to throw metric on the other side but I just couldn't do it. I work in the custom fabrication industry in Canada. Canada is officially speaking metric but people who build things out of 4' x 8' plywood don't really want to make a leap to 1200 x 2400 mm ply. In may ways, a base 12 measurement system is easier from a pedestrian perspective- 12 breaks down evenly into 2,6,3 and 4 whereas base 10 one just has 2 and 5. Ultimately, it is just what one is used to. No one I work with is happy when they see millimeters on a drawing or mm on a tape measure- we toss the dual system tapes back in the bin. We describe weather in celsius and distance in kilometers but we build things in feet and inches and that will take a long time to change. Long winded but that's why I didn't put the strip of metric on the other side : )

title: Glass Bed Clamp for Printrbot Simple Metal w/ Heated Bed

description.text:
After looking at various glass bed clips, I determined that none of them were right for the very thick heated bed of the Printrbot Simple Metal. Therefore, I fired up my copy of Fusion 360 and, 14 revisions later, had something that fit my needs.

Update: The versions that I printed in ABS worked for about a month and then became ineffective due to fatigue. I've printed a new set out of PETG which also hold quite well and will try to report on their performance over time.

Further Update: The PETG printed versions remained effective for close to a year, so that's my current recommended material.

Design constraints included:

  • 25mm bed thickness
  • 30mm from edge of bed to glass
  • 3mm glass thickness
  • 14mm lip at the bottom of the bed

The resulting clip allows the bed to have a full range of motion and holds tightly to both the bed and the glass. It should probably work decently for different glass thicknesses.

It's been designed to print in ABS or PETG -- other materials may not have the correct flexibility and heat tolerance. I printed it with 15% infill and a single 0.8mm perimeter, but it will probably work fine with your favorite settings as well.

I've been making some specialty laser cut vanity plates and needed an easy way to show them off, so I sat down and threw this stand together in about 15 minutes.  Simple but functional.
Pretty simple design, just cut and assemble.

I like the Thing but wondered if you could print the whole Thing without requiring extra hardware (the bolt and nut).
And so here it is. Its made to fit my mandolin's heads, but should fit a guitar too.

Just print. You may need to use a thin blade to free the 2 parts. There are 3 versions, one with tight tolerance (0.5mm and 0.25). The other 2 have bit larger (1mm, called MachineHeadWinder_Blocky_MoreClearance.STL).
MachineHeadWinder_V3.STL has a larger 'socket'. Haven't tried raftless but it should work. For UP!ers : use the original tight model. Printed at 0.25mm, default support. loose fill(?)(1 down from solid)

comments.text: ToM w/Mk7, printed with neither raft nor support (3 extra shells, 50% infill, otherwise default settings. Could probably lose a shell). The bridging was a little sloppy the first layer or two, but firmed up nicely afterwards (top). I just scraped out the odd bits from those layers (bottom). The lost plastic doesn't seem to have a meaningful impact on the winder's final strength.
